## Submit accounting adjustments

When the customer has submitted all quarterly updates, they may need to make an accounting adjustment to their income or expenses. The [Business Source Adjustable Summary API](https://developer.service.hmrc.gov.uk/api-documentation/docs/api/service/self-assessment-bsas-api/) enables a customer to submit or retrieve an adjustable summary calculation for a specified self-employment or property business.

> If a customer submits an annual or quarterly update after making BSAS adjustments, their submitted adjustments become invalid. They will need to make their BSAS adjustments again.
>
> If a customer has multiple agents who make BSAS adjustments, the latest adjustments will overwrite earlier adjustments.

The adjustments should be submitted as a positive or negative amount. For example, if a customer has already submitted advertising costs of £250 but the figure should be £200, the adjustment required would be -50. Adjustments are always made against the total of the original quarterly updates. Each new adjustment will overwrite the previous adjustment as shown in the table below.

| | Original (total of all 4 quarters) | 1<sup>st</sup> adjustment | Revised total | 2<sup>nd</sup> adjustment | Revised total |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| premisesRunningCosts | 500 | 25 | 525 | 23 | 523 |
| travelCosts          | 600 | -17 | 583 | -20 | 580 |

To make an accounting adjustment, the software needs to call the [Trigger a Business Source Adjustable Summary](https://developer.service.hmrc.gov.uk/api-documentation/docs/api/service/self-assessment-bsas-api/7.0/oas/page#/paths/~1individuals~1self-assessment~1adjustable-summary~1{nino}~1trigger/post) endpoint to receive the calculation ID. The software will need to provide this calculation ID when submitting any adjustments to HMRC using the following endpoints:

- [Submit Self-Employment Accounting Adjustments](https://developer.service.hmrc.gov.uk/api-documentation/docs/api/service/self-assessment-bsas-api/7.0/oas/page#tag/Self-employment-business/paths/~1individuals~1self-assessment~1adjustable-summary~1{nino}~1self-employment~1{calculationId}~1adjust/post)
- [Submit UK Property Accounting Adjustments](https://developer.service.hmrc.gov.uk/api-documentation/docs/api/service/self-assessment-bsas-api/7.0/oas/page#tag/UK-property-business/paths/~1individuals~1self-assessment~1adjustable-summary~1{nino}~1uk-property~1{calculationId}~1adjust/post)
- [Submit Foreign Property Accounting Adjustments](https://developer.service.hmrc.gov.uk/api-documentation/docs/api/service/self-assessment-bsas-api/7.0/oas/page#tag/Foreign-property-business/paths/~1individuals~1self-assessment~1adjustable-summary~1{nino}~1foreign-property~1{calculationId}~1adjust/post)

When an adjustment has been made, the customer can view a summary. To retrieve this, the software should call any of the following endpoints, using the same calculation ID:

- [Retrieve a Self-Employment Business Source Adjustable Summary (BSAS)](https://developer.service.hmrc.gov.uk/api-documentation/docs/api/service/self-assessment-bsas-api/7.0/oas/page#tag/Self-employment-business/paths/~1individuals~1self-assessment~1adjustable-summary~1{nino}~1self-employment~1{calculationId}/get)[ ](https://developer.service.hmrc.gov.uk/api-documentation/docs/api/service/self-assessment-bsas-api/7.0/oas/page#tag/Self-employment-business/paths/~1individuals~1self-assessment~1adjustable-summary~1{nino}~1self-employment~1{calculationId}~1adjust/post)
- [Retrieve a UK Property Business Source Adjustable Summary (BSAS)](https://developer.service.hmrc.gov.uk/api-documentation/docs/api/service/self-assessment-bsas-api/7.0/oas/page#tag/UK-property-business/paths/~1individuals~1self-assessment~1adjustable-summary~1{nino}~1uk-property~1{calculationId}/get)
- [Retrieve a Foreign Property Business Source Adjustable Summary (BSAS)](https://developer.service.hmrc.gov.uk/api-documentation/docs/api/service/self-assessment-bsas-api/7.0/oas/page#tag/Foreign-property-business/paths/~1individuals~1self-assessment~1adjustable-summary~1{nino}~1foreign-property~1{calculationId}/get)

### Non-aligned taxpayers

Non-aligned taxpayers are customers with periods of account, or accounting periods, that do not end on either 31st March or 1-5th April of the tax year.

These taxpayers will need to calculate their taxable profit for the tax year outside MTD in addition to their MTD journey.

During the tax year, non-aligned taxpayers use software to maintain and keep digital records and submit quarterly updates aligned to the tax year. Taxpayers will need to start keeping digital records from the start of any accounting period which will end in the tax year.

After the end of the accounting period that ends in the tax year, non-aligned taxpayers prepare their accounts for that period, including calculating the taxable profit. The customer will then calculate the proportion of the accounting period’s taxable profit belonging to the tax year based on the number of days in the period that falls in the tax year. The portion calculated as falling within the tax year constitutes the first part of the taxable profit for the tax year.

After the end of the tax year and submission of the final cumulative quarterly update for that tax year, non-aligned taxpayers must submit any accounting adjustments and other relevant allowances and adjustments that were included in the period of account that ended in the tax year, using the [Business Source Adjustable Summary](https://developer.service.hmrc.gov.uk/api-documentation/docs/api/service/self-assessment-bsas-api/7.0/oas/page) API and the [Self Employment Annual Submission API](https://developer.service.hmrc.gov.uk/api-documentation/docs/api/service/self-employment-business-api/5.0/oas/page#tag/Self-Employment-Annual-Submission/paths/~1individuals~1business~1self-employment~1%7Bnino%7D~1%7BbusinessId%7D~1annual~1%7BtaxYear%7D/put) respectively. This will result in a figure made up of information from the final cumulative quarterly update which is aligned to the tax year, and tax adjustments for the first accounting period which is not aligned to the tax year. The figure can be viewed using the [Business Income Source Summary API](https://developer.service.hmrc.gov.uk/api-documentation/docs/api/service/self-assessment-biss-api/3.0/oas/page#/paths/~1individuals~1self-assessment~1income-summary~1%7Bnino%7D~1%7BtypeOfBusiness%7D~1%7BtaxYear%7D~1%7BbusinessId%7D/get).

After the end of the second accounting period (which extends beyond the tax year) non-aligned taxpayers prepare their accounts for that period including calculating the taxable profit. The taxpayer will then calculate the proportion of the accounting period’s taxable profit belonging to the tax year based on the number of days in the period that falls in the tax year. The portion calculated as falling within the tax year constitutes the second part of the taxable profit for the tax year. This should be added to the first part of the taxable profit for the tax year, identified earlier, to obtain the full taxable profit for the tax year. The figure obtained by triggering the Business Income Source Summary API should be subtracted from the full taxable profit for the tax year to identify the tax year basis adjustment balancing figure. The basis adjustment balancing figure should then be submitted using the basis adjustment data item in the [Self Employment Annual Submission API](https://developer.service.hmrc.gov.uk/api-documentation/docs/api/service/self-employment-business-api/5.0/oas/page#tag/Self-Employment-Annual-Submission/paths/~1individuals~1business~1self-employment~1%7Bnino%7D~1%7BbusinessId%7D~1annual~1%7BtaxYear%7D/put). This will ensure that the taxable profit for the tax year is reflected accurately. Customers must check that the result of submitting the basis adjustment balancing figure is the same as the taxable profit calculated outside MTD.

Customers with accounting dates later in the calendar year may have to estimate the provisional profits for the second accounting period if their set of accounts won’t be ready in time for the tax year’s filing deadline. These customers would need to submit an amendment to their return when confirmed figures become available.

